Discover the magic of mathematics with this simple JavaScript function that calculates the square root of a number using the Babylonian method! Try it out and watch the estimate get closer and closer to the actual square root.

```javascript
function calculateSquareRoot(num) {
  if (num < 0) return "Error: Negative numbers do not have real square roots.";
  if (num === 0) return 0;
  let x = num;
  while (true) {
    const new_x = (x + num / x) / 2;
    if (Math.abs(new_x - x) < 0.0001) {
      return new_x;
    }
    x = new_x;
  }
}
```

This iterative method, also known as Heron's method, is a fun and engaging way to deepen your understanding of square roots!

Feeling proud, let's write a Java function to check if a given binary tree is a binary search tree (BST). Our `isBST` function takes in the root node and calls a helper function `isBSTHelper` with the minimum and maximum integer values.

```java
public boolean isBST(Node root) {
    return isBSTHelper(root, Integer.MIN_VALUE, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
}

private boolean isBSTHelper(Node node, int min, int max) {
    if (node == null) {
        return true;
    }
    if (node.data < min || node.data > max) {
        return false;
    }
    return isBSTHelper(node.left, min, node.data - 1) && isBSTHelper(node.right, node.data + 1, max);
}
```

The `isBSTHelper` function checks if the node is null and returns true. If the node's value violates the BST property by being less than min or greater than max, it returns false. Otherwise, it recursively checks the left and right subtrees with updated min and max values. When both subtrees return true, the overall function returns true, making us proud of our BST!

